build outputs.\n\n```diff\n--- /dev/null\n+++ /home/perrymckay1/.gitignore\n@@ -0,0 +1,12 @@\n+# Dependencies\n+node_modules/\n+\n+# Environment variables (CRITICAL)\n+.env\n+\n+# Build output\n+dist/\n+\n+# Test coverage \u0026 artifacts\n+cypress/videos/\n+cypress/screenshots/\n```\n\n### 2. Initialize and Push Your Code\nIf you haven't initialized a Git repository yet, run the following commands in your terminal:\n\n```bash\n# Initialize the git repository\ngit init\n\n# Stage your files (the .gitignore will prevent .env from being staged)\ngit add .\n\n# Commit your code\ngit commit -m \"Initial commit: Set up Express backend, UI components, and test suites\"\n\n# Rename the default branch to main (if necessary)\ngit branch -M main\n\n# Add your GitHub repository as the remote origin (replace with your actual GitHub URL)\ngit remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/your-repo-name.git\n\n# Push the code to GitHub\ngit push -u origin main\n```\n\n### 3. Set Up Continuous Integration (GitHub Actions)\nSince you have an excellent suite of Jest tests and Cypress tests, you should configure GitHub to run these tests automatically every time you push code or create a Pull Request. This ensures you never accidentally break your app.\n\nCreate a GitHub Actions workflow file:\n\n```diff\n--- /dev/null\n+++ /home/perrymckay1/.github/workflows/ci.yml\n@@ -0,0 +1,30 @@\n+name: Freight App CI\n+\n+on:\n+  push:\n+    branches: [ \"main\" ]\n+  pull_request:\n+    branches: [ \"main\" ]\n+\n+jobs:\n+  test:\n+    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n+\n+    steps:\n+    - name: Checkout code\n+      uses: actions/checkout@v3\n+      \n+    - name: Set up Node.js\n+      uses: actions/setup-node@v3\n+      with:\n+        node-version: '18.x'\n+        cache: 'npm'\n+        \n+    - name: Install dependencies\n+      run: npm ci\n+      \n+    - name: Build frontend\n+      run: node build.js\n+      \n+    - name: Run Jest Unit Tests\n+      run: npm test\n```\n*(Note: If your `package.json` uses a different test command or you want to add a specific Cypress testing step using the `cypress-io/github-action`, you can expand on this later!)*\n\n### 4. Configure GitHub Secrets\nFor your tests or deployments to run properly in the cloud later, they might need access to environment variables. \n1. Go to your repository on GitHub.\n2. Click **Settings** \u003e **Secrets and variables** \u003e **Actions**.\n3. Add any necessary non-production test keys here (like a Stripe Test Secret Key) so your GitHub Actions can safely use them during automated testing.\n\nOnce this is pushed, GitHub will serve as your backup, your version history, and your automated testing pipeline!\n\n\u003c!--\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]How do I add my Cypress E2E tests to the GitHub Actions workflow?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n[PROMPT_SUGGESTION]Can you help me write a README.md file for this project's GitHub page?[/PROMPT_SUGGESTION]\n--\u003e","chatSectionId":"0","ideContext":{"currentFile":{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/app_flow.cy.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"CURRENTLY_OPEN"},"remoteContexts":null,"remoteRepositories":[],"otherFiles":[{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/bids.test.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"COLOCATED"},{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/commonSchemas.test.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"COLOCATED"},{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/notifications.test.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"COLOCATED"},{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/adminReferrals.test.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"COLOCATED"},{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/passwordForms.test.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"COLOCATED"},{"path":"/home/perrymckay1/passwordForms.js","language":"javascript","selection":{"start":0,"end":0},"includedReason":"COLOCATED"},{"path":"/home